<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="decimalexpansions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Decimal Expansions</title>

  <p> 
    Our main goal in this chapter is to understand ways of using rational numbers to approximate real numbers.
    The most common way of doing this is to use decimal expansions, which is a technique that you first learn in elementary or middle school.
    For example, most of you are familiar with the idea that
    <md>
      \pi=3.14\ldots
    </md>
    has an infinite, non-repeating decimal expansion, and that
    <md>
      \frac{1}{3}=0.333\ldots
    </md>
    has an infinite, repeating decimal expansion.
    In this section, we will prove several properties of decimal expansions.  
  </p>

